After showing in the first ode the vanity of power and riches‚ Horace here takes up a positive theme.

‘Content with small estate the Roman youth should learn courage in the stern school of war, that he may fight for Rome and die for her if need be3 death for one's native land is sweet and gloriou53 and the coward may not escape the common fate (1-16). True manhood is secure and independent of popular favor3 it alone gives immortality (17—24). Fidelity and silence too have their secure reward. The wicked punishment sooner or later overtakes (2 5—32).' Mene, 68.
